;;; 02-training-signals-and-data.slat — SRE Manual · Chapter 02 ·
;;; Reading training curves as signals about the corpus.
;;;
;;; When training runs, its loss trajectory says something about the
;;; corpus at every iter range. Different rates give you different
;;; signals. This chapter is the runbook for reading the graph in
;;; real time and knowing what to do at each moment.
;;;
;;; Written 2026-07-19 during Motoi Mk 1 fire. Every rate + threshold
;;; below is anchored to a real Motoi generation reveal (Mk A / Mk B).

(dialect :applies ("motoi-eng") :note "SRE Manual — reading training signals.")

(chapter
  :number   "02"
  :title    "Training signals: reading curves as data quality reports"
  :book     "SRE Manual"
  :written  "2026-07-19"
  :audience ("sre" "training-pipeline" "engineering" "human-operator")
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "internal-eng"
  :prerequisites ("01-forge-preflight-and-fire.slat"))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 1 — The frame
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Every training run produces two loss curves — train and val. Most
;; operators watch them fall and hope for the best. That's fine, but
;; the curves are actually TELLING YOU THINGS about your corpus at
;; different rates. If you know what to listen for at each range,
;; you can:
;;
;;   · Kill a bad run in the first 100 iters instead of the first hour.
;;   · Diagnose corpus problems before you spend cycles evaluating.
;;   · Predict the reveal outcome before it happens.
;;
;; The runbook below organizes the signals by iter-range because each
;; range answers a different question. Read down; each section builds
;; on the one above.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 2 — Iter 1 (val loss cold start) — how far your data is from base
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   The base model has never seen your corpus. Iter 1 val loss is
;;   how confused it is on your held-out sample. Nothing has been
;;   trained yet — this is the pre-training baseline.
;;
;; Motoi Mk 1 (Qwen2.5-Coder-1.5B-Instruct on our validation):
;;   Iter 1 val loss = 3.12
;;
;; Interpretation range for a 1.5B code-tuned base:
;;   < 2.0    the base already speaks your domain (rare — polish only)
;;   2.0–3.5  normal cold start — your data is adjacent to what base saw
;;   3.5–5.0  distant domain — you're teaching something the base did not see
;;   > 5.0    very distant, or your validation set is malformed. Investigate.
;;
;; When to act at iter 1:
;;   · NaN or ∞ — model isn't loading. Kill, fix config.
;;   · > 10.0  — likely tokenizer misalignment or malformed valid.jsonl.
;;               Kill, run preflight on valid.jsonl.
;;   · The number itself — take note. It's the baseline. Every drop
;;     below iter 1 is the model learning.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 3 — Iters 10–100 (warmup) — is the corpus LEARNABLE at all
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   During warmup, the learning rate ramps from ~0 to peak (default
;;   1e-4). The model is starting to move. If your data has any
;;   coherent signal, train loss will drop sharply in log-scale.
;;
;; What a healthy drop looks like:
;;   Iter 10:  train loss 4.0-4.5 (still random-ish)
;;   Iter 50:  train loss 3.0-3.5 (finding shape)
;;   Iter 100: train loss 2.5-3.0 (learning begins)
;;
;; Motoi Mk 1 actual (2026-07-19):
;;   Iter 10:  4.043
;;   Iter 100: ~2.5 (steady descent)
;;
;; Failure modes at this range:
;;   · Flat train loss (bounces around iter-1 value) — DATA IS NOISE.
;;     Your corpus has no coherent signal. Contradictions, malformed
;;     pairs, or the model has no capacity to learn what you fed it.
;;     Kill within 200 iters. Do not wait for a checkpoint.
;;
;;   · Loss RISES steadily — LR too high, or your corpus is fighting
;;     the base (e.g., you're teaching the base a language that
;;     contradicts what it already knows). Kill, halve LR, refire.
;;
;;   · Loss oscillates wildly (2.5, 5.5, 2.8, 6.1, …) — batch size
;;     too small, or corpus has subclusters that fight each other.
;;     Investigate.
;;
;; When to act:
;;   Every 10-iter mark is a heartbeat. If you see 5 consecutive
;;   heartbeats with no descent below iter-1 value, kill.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 4 — Iters 200–2000 (early cosine descent) — SHAPE of the corpus
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   Warmup is done, LR is at peak, cosine decay begins. The model
;;   is now consuming the corpus's structural signal. The RATE of
;;   descent tells you how much SHAPE the corpus has.
;;
;; Healthy shapes:
;;   · Steep continued descent — the corpus has wide, deep signal.
;;     Model has a lot to learn. This is what you want.
;;     Motoi Mk B (2.0) hit this: train loss dropped ~2.5 → ~1.5
;;     between iter 500 and iter 2500.
;;
;;   · Rapid plateau — the corpus is thin. Model absorbed the pattern
;;     in a few hundred iters and now has nothing more to learn.
;;     Train loss flattens at 2.0-2.5 and stays there.
;;     Meaning: your corpus taught a narrow shape. Fine if that was
;;     the goal (e.g., a safety-only run). Bad if you expected broad
;;     acquisition.
;;
;;   · Bumps and spikes — the corpus has internal contradictions.
;;     Subgroups of pairs teach different things. Model oscillates
;;     between them. Investigate: do you have Row 4 invariants that
;;     disagree? Do you have safety pairs that contradict persona
;;     pairs?
;;
;; When to act:
;;   · If descent stops at 2.0+ by iter 1000, corpus is thin. You can
;;     let it run (no harm) but expect a shallow reveal.
;;   · If descent continues below 1.5 by iter 2000, corpus is dense.
;;     Reveal will be interesting. Prepare probe suite.
;;   · If curves are bumpy, save a checkpoint and probe it manually.
;;     Something is fighting.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 5 — Train vs Val delta (any point after warmup) — generalization
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   Train loss = wrong on batches the model IS learning from.
;;   Val loss = wrong on batches it has NEVER seen (held out).
;;   The gap between them tells you whether the model is generalizing
;;   or memorizing.
;;
;; Healthy patterns:
;;   · Train and val track together, both dropping. Generalization.
;;     Model learns shape, not specifics. This is what you want.
;;
;;   · Val slightly above train (0.1-0.3 delta), both dropping.
;;     Normal. Val is always a bit harder because model hasn't
;;     seen it before.
;;
;;   · Val BELOW train — validation set is easier than train, or
;;     val set is too small (< 1000 pairs is suspect). Not
;;     necessarily a problem, but interpret with caution.
;;
;; Failure patterns:
;;   · Train drops, val flat. OVERFITTING. Model is memorizing
;;     training set. Two causes usually: (a) corpus too small for
;;     the LoRA rank (r=128 with 6k pairs is at the edge of this),
;;     (b) too many epochs. Kill at the last-good val checkpoint.
;;
;;   · Train drops, val RISES. Severe overfitting. Kill immediately,
;;     use earlier checkpoint, reduce epochs or add data.
;;
;;   · Both drop but val curve is choppy while train is smooth.
;;     Val set has subclusters not well-represented in train. Not
;;     fatal but worth investigating post-run.
;;
;; When to act:
;;   Check the delta every 500-1000 iters. If val diverges from
;;   train for more than 2000 consecutive iters, kill and roll back
;;   to the last checkpoint where they were still together.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 6 — Every save_every checkpoint — the REAL data question
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   Loss curves are useful but LIE BY OMISSION. A loss of 1.5 tells
;;   you "closer to something." It does NOT tell you WHAT the model
;;   learned to produce.
;;
;; The real question — DID THE MODEL ACQUIRE THE SHAPES YOU WANTED?
;;   Only checkpoint probes answer this.
;;
;; Every save_every (default 500), an adapter checkpoint lands at:
;;   ~/.forge/runs/motoi-<gen>/adapter/{iter}_adapters.safetensors
;;
;; The probe protocol:
;;
;;   1. Load the checkpoint into an inference server (llama.cpp,
;;      llm/serve, or mlx_lm.generate — whichever your ops uses).
;;
;;   2. Run a fixed probe suite of ~10-40 prompts. The suite should
;;      be your ROW-BY-ROW test:
;;         Row 1 probe: "How do I use vec/dot?" (composition shape)
;;         Row 2 probe: "When would I reach for hash-set! vs assq?"
;;                      (audit shape)
;;         Row 3 probe: "Where else does map's shape appear?"
;;                      (dimension shape)
;;         Row 4 probe: "Why does transpose(transpose(M)) = M?"
;;                      (proof shape)
;;         Row 5 probe: "What emerges when I chain remember! + recall?"
;;                      (emergence shape)
;;
;;   3. Score each response subjectively AND objectively:
;;         · Objective: does it produce runnable code?
;;         · Objective: does it name the CS pattern (Row 4/5)?
;;         · Subjective: does it feel like Motoi (persona voice)?
;;         · Subjective: does it stay in the row's lane?
;;
;;   4. Log the probe results in the run's `_status/probes/iter-N.md`.
;;
;; The probe results are what tells you WHICH row shapes are landing.
;; Loss just says "closer to something" — probes tell you WHAT.
;;
;; When to act:
;;   · Row-shape acquisition detected → keep running.
;;   · Row-shape absent by iter 5000 → data may not be teaching that
;;     shape. Investigate: is Row 4 present in the corpus? What's
;;     its per-verb proportion?
;;   · Row-shape learned then LOST → later data is displacing earlier.
;;     Reorder corpus.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 7 — End of epoch 1 — what actually stuck after one full pass
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   The model has now seen every pair in your corpus exactly once.
;;   Val loss at end-of-epoch-1 tells you the "steady state" learning
;;   the corpus offers.
;;
;; For Motoi Mk 1 at 109,398 train rows with effective_batch 4:
;;   end of epoch 1 = iter 27,350
;;
;; Interpretation:
;;   · Val loss at end-of-epoch-1 still steeply dropping → corpus
;;     has more to teach; epoch 2 and 3 will move the model further.
;;   · Val loss at end-of-epoch-1 plateaued → the corpus taught what
;;     it can teach. More epochs will polish but not add. Cost/benefit
;;     tips toward stopping early and iterating on data.
;;   · Val loss at end-of-epoch-1 UP from a prior floor → overfitting
;;     started. Roll back to last-good checkpoint.
;;
;; Motoi Mk B (2.0) as reference — successful past run:
;;   End of epoch 1 val loss (approx): ~1.6
;;   End of epoch 2 val loss (approx): ~1.4
;;   End of epoch 3 val loss (approx): ~1.3
;;   Diminishing returns pattern — third epoch was polish.
;;
;; When to act:
;;   Take a checkpoint at end-of-epoch-1 no matter what. That's your
;;   "one clean pass" baseline. If epoch 2 goes off the rails, roll
;;   back here.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 8 — Epoch 2 vs epoch 1 delta — corpus density
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   In epoch 2, the model sees every pair a SECOND time. If it drops
;;   loss further, the corpus rewarded repetition — it has dense
;;   patterns worth reinforcing. If it stays flat, the corpus was
;;   fully absorbed in one pass — dense information but shallow reward.
;;
;; Metrics:
;;   Δ(epoch 2 - epoch 1 val) < 0 by 0.1+ → dense corpus, epochs help
;;   Δ ≈ 0                                → thin corpus, saturated
;;   Δ > 0                                → overfitting; roll back
;;
;; Motoi Mk B (2.0):
;;   epoch 1 → epoch 2 val loss delta: ~-0.2 (healthy dense corpus)
;;   epoch 2 → epoch 3 val loss delta: ~-0.1 (polish only)
;;
;; When to act:
;;   · Δ < 0.05 between epoch 1 and epoch 2 — kill after epoch 1,
;;     don't waste compute on epoch 2 or 3.
;;   · Δ > 0.15 — corpus is very dense, could benefit from a
;;     fourth epoch. Update config, refire.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 9 — Learning rate + loss coupling (advanced signal)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   As cosine decay reduces LR, loss should still drop but at a
;;   slower rate. If loss KEEPS dropping fast even at low LR, the
;;   corpus has residual learnable signal you're leaving on the
;;   table. If loss STOPS dropping the moment LR decays, the corpus
;;   was operating at the ceiling of what LR could learn.
;;
;; The heuristic:
;;   Rate of loss descent per unit LR = "learn efficiency"
;;   High efficiency at end of run → data richer than budget allows
;;   Low efficiency at end of run → data absorbed within budget
;;
;; When to act:
;;   · If loss is still dropping at iter 60000/82000 (75%),
;;     consider extending iters by 20-30%. Corpus wants more time.
;;   · If loss plateau'd by iter 40000, don't extend. Kill at plateau.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 10 — Cross-generation comparison — the "am I on trajectory?" check
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; What it measures:
;;   Every Motoi generation gives you an anchor point. Overlay your
;;   current curve on Mk B (2.0)'s curve. If they're similar shape,
;;   you're on the same track. If different shape, your data is
;;   fundamentally different from Mk B's — new territory.
;;
;; Anchor points from past reveals (see MOTOI-3-GENERATIONS-REFERENCE):
;;
;;   Mk A (0.75, iter 65000 approx):
;;     · val loss ~1.4
;;     · perplexity mean 4.457, median 3.436
;;
;;   Mk B (2.0, iter 77020):
;;     · val loss ~1.3
;;     · perplexity mean 3.367 (−24% from Mk A)
;;     · safety-emergency 0.025 → 0.65 (25× improvement)
;;     · non-Scheme resistance 0.60 → 1.00 (full pass)
;;
;;   Mk 1 (2026-07-19, iter 82049 target):
;;     · val loss target: on Mk B trajectory or better
;;     · reveal: to be measured after checkpoint
;;
;; When to act:
;;   · Below Mk B's trajectory (better val at same iter) → strong
;;     corpus; the reference-manual polish is landing.
;;   · Above Mk B's trajectory → weaker corpus. Investigate: is the
;;     row-uniform shape less densely-informative than Mk B's
;;     concentrated bucket shape?
;;   · Very different shape (steep-fall-fast-plateau vs slow-continuous) →
;;     you're teaching a new pattern the historical trajectory doesn't
;;     predict. Novel territory.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 11 — What to do at each rate: quick-reference table
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;;   IterRange     WhatItTellsYou                                 Action
;;   ────────    ──────────────────────────────────────         ────────
;;   1           Baseline confusion (how far from base)          Note it
;;   10–100      Warmup — is data learnable at all               Kill if flat
;;   200–2000    Shape of corpus (steep vs plateau)              Assess density
;;   2000–5000   First save_every checkpoints — probe            Run probe suite
;;   ~end epoch 1 What actually stuck after one pass             Take baseline
;;   epoch 2 delta Corpus density (repetition reward)            Decide epoch 3
;;   final iter  Learning efficiency / whether budget was right  Extend or not
;;   Cross-gen   Am I on Mk B trajectory                         Compare curves

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 12 — The one rule that overrides all of the above
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Loss curves are a proxy. Checkpoint probes are ground truth. If
;; probes at iter 5000 show the row shapes landing well, keep running
;; regardless of what the loss curve is doing. If probes at iter 5000
;; show garbage, kill regardless of how good the loss curve looks.
;;
;; The purpose of reading the loss curve is to DECIDE WHEN TO PROBE.
;; It is not a substitute for probing. Never train blind past a
;; checkpoint you haven't sampled.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; End of chapter 02.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
